meta {
  name: GET privileges (per-user subscription + capabilities for a vehicle)
  type: http
  seq: 4
}

get {
  url: https://b-h-s.spr.{{country}}00.p.con-veh.net/rrs/v1/privileges/user/{{user_id}}/vehicle/{{vehicle_uuid}}
  body: none
  auth: bearer
}

auth:bearer {
  token: {{access_token}}
}

headers {
  Accept: application/json
  Content-Type: application/json
  User-Agent: MyVW/1.0 Android
}

docs {
  v2.10.0 (Group C). VW North America Cox-backend privileges endpoint.

  Returns the per-vehicle subscription + capability map for the signed-in
  user. Reference: zackcornelius/CarConnectivity-connector-volkswagen-na
  scan 2026-06-02.

  Response shape (sanitised from the NA app traffic):

    {
      "data": {
        "subscription": {
          "active": true,
          "expiresAt": "2027-08-14T00:00:00Z"
        },
        "capabilities": {
          "remoteLockUnlock": "ENABLED",
          "preTripClimate": "ENABLED"
        }
      }
    }

  NA-specific shape vs EU:

  - EU CARIAD-BFF exposes the same information via
    ``/vehicle/v1/vehicles/{vin}/userCapabilities`` with a fundamentally
    different envelope (capabilitiesStatus.value[*].expirationDate per
    capability).
  - NA aggregates into a single subscription block per vehicle plus a
    flat capabilities map. The earliest-expiry aggregation that the EU
    parser does is not needed here.
  - Endpoint is addressed by user_id + vehicle_uuid rather than VIN.

  Soft-fail contract: 401 / 403 / 404 / 5xx leave the cross-brand
  ``subscription_active`` + ``subscription_expiry_at`` + ``capabilities_count``
  fields at None so phantom-protection hides the sensors for accounts
  without the entitlement.
}
